It's been quite a long time since I actually bothered to set up my own blog or site, and while the amount of tools available now dwarfs what you can find in mid 2000s, I found the hidden amount of complexity today can also be significant due to expanding limit of possibilities. Fixing mistakes can easily ended up being over-engineered in nature if you're not careful, and it's easy to be misled by the promise of easy starts & few clicks to complete. 
Luckily this is just a personal site so destructive & irreversible steps aren't expensive, in fact practically 0 amount of money involved if time & internet bandwidth aren't counted as cost. But still, although fast & cheap (or free) do _saves_ time, beware that _cheap resources frequently incentivised recklessness_, and that certainly _can be bad in engineering_ projects. Arguably it also applies to any project with enough complexity. 

That said what I'm experiencing is an example of how poor planning of a project can lead to complicated mess that makes it more expensive than initial prediction, especially if mixed with technical debt ignorance. Avoiding 'move fast break things' philosophy can be quite hard to do these days. So I thought I should log it for future reference.  


### Plan

Build a site with these requirements:

1. Simple blog feature for taxonomy URLs, easily linked page for personal projects & informations, nothing unusual.  
2. Static files instead of database backend. 
3. Easy to maintain: markdown support, git based.
4. Free, moving to own domain be done painlessly. 
5. CI/CD environment, API richness is a must.

Github Pages certainly is the obvious choice, but I didn't do enough research/preparations especially on git & CI/CD. I think the factors of zero cost & abundance of available tech gadgets induced my attitude to start as soon as possible, as fast as possible & experiment along the way. Not wrong in this particular case as mentioned, but certainly worthy to emphasise again. 

### Descent to the mess

My steps to achieve the requirements:
1. Chose Hugo as static site CMS generator, not using JS stack (ugh) or Django.
2. Use Hugo Docker image instead of installing Go & whatnot (I use [`klakegg/hugo:0.62.1-ext-alpine`](https://github.com/oleng/hugo_github/blob/master/docker-compose.yml)).
3. Created github.io repo 
4. Spent some time figuring out how Hugo works in terms of folder structures & configs, play around with the themes, include paths, etc. Minimum amount of git exploration here aside from usual clone/pull, commit & push. I figured with `github-pages` bot in place for Pages repos I only need to push the HTML files (in `public/` folder by default) to Github. That is correct but as later I found, was short sighted.
5. Manual deployment with `docker exec --it hugo bash` in another terminal window and then `hugo -v`, thought I can switch to CI/CD along the way without much efforts.

All good so far, I've done most of the work, plumbing laid out, site is up, just need to configure Hugo's taxonomy  correctly, which once done will be reflected automatically in future deployments since they're just static files.

It didn't take a few days for having to manually push the build on every single post or edit to really bothers me. D'oh. What are the choices then? Certainly in order to have full CI/CD pipeline on the cloud, I need to have Hugo folders in a remote repo as well instead of just static files for Github to serve. My first mistake was I didn't know enough about CD for Hugo or Github CI/CD options (it can be Gitlab or Gitbucket, too) to know what this means, or what alternatives I could've had taken. So I made a conclusion jump that the cleanest way to do this is to have a separate repo for Hugo files, then have an automated service triggering build process to push the static files to my github.io repo. Sounds logical isn't it? Jump straight back to experiment boat!

I made a separate repo just for Hugo. Several, in fact. I found some services and skimmed through their docs for a couple of hours before decided to try a few. A lot of the complications are mostly stemmed from the fact that I want to keep the built files in my github repo,  may not be a dealbreaking if I use my own domain. I tried Netlify (which is promising and probably very complete feature wise for anyone else), but I can't use Github pages as domain. I like forestry with their very straight forward & git based approach, they're supposed to tick all the boxes by allowing user to deploy to point to Github repo, but unfortunately (and understandably) they stopped that deployment feature starting this year. Oh well, there goes a day wasted.

Time to rethink, I turned back to git. What if I can have `public` folder in Hugo repo that points out to my github.io repo? Of course it's possible, using [git submodule](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Tools-Submodules) effectively I have a clone of another repo in a folder. That's easy enough to implement. 

Back to CI/CD, there are two ways to do this. First you can use a [shell script described in Hugo's online doc](https://gohugo.io/hosting-and-deployment/hosting-on-github/) to automate it (_Yes, I'm an idiot_.) But this is still just shortening my manual steps of executing Hugo build, what I want is each of my markdown entry git push to trigger automatic build & deploy, an actual CI/CD. The thought of scripting in bash made me groan a bit so I abandoned the thought of modifying (completing) the shell script.

Second, there are Github Actions for Hugo available. D'oh(2). One of them is from the author of that dockerimage I used. _Note: Github Action is basically shell scripts for automating build processes on Github server(s) using Dockerfile_.

One good thing I did though, was to open an issue ticket for documenting this. I'll go over at the end why this is good.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

So I tested it, the build passed as success but nothing seemed to happen. By this point I subconciously didn't want to spend more time & efforts so I moved faster, switched to another Hugo Github Action, just following the instructions, and tested it. This one requires SSH keys to deploy so I like it better, and this time there was actual deployment, but in the wrong branch. I both cheered & cursed myself, so I stopped a bit to examine it more carefully. I found the Action build logs.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)


### Post Mortem

I think I kind of understood by then, that I should've looked around at Github to learn what resource is available for deploying Hugo in the first place. Failing that, I also should've kept Hugo folders with `public` folder in a single repo before jumping to more complex solution. Or in other words keep things simple, just like how I envisioned it: should be easy to maintain. Lure of ready-to-use stacks & my less than vigilant approach led me astray. Separate repo & submodule decisions were major mistakes, mostly over-engineered solution since it added complexity in future development without real necessity. And even if it works, I can't see how the benefits outweigh the drawbacks in this case.



I also failed to using solution like Notion for documenting your every steps as dev/build logs is recommended, seeing your steps in a single place is great way to catch mistakes & misconceptions faster, or when you need to rethink your strategy.
